			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Hi.  Oz from Wa. State here again... (oh's N0ZZ3Rz!!!  RunZ!!! HidZ!!!).
<br />
  I think that this type of recount could be valuable overall.  Why?  Because in our state we had the Governors race come down to 261 votes, which triggered an automatic machine recount that resulted in a revised victory of 42 votes for the initial winner, a Republican.  That's 42 votes in 2.8+Million cast.  The machine recount found over 2500 votes that weren't counted, and resulted in changes that in any one of several counties would have swung the election.  Either way.
<br />

<br />
Now we are in for round #3.  The hand recount.  Expected to take until Born-Jesus day, this one was funded by the Democrats to do a recount that will be final (because state law requires that they pay for it... unless if when they are done it is changed, then they get their money back).  If the Republicans lose, then they can ask for another recount.  And when they win that one, then the Democrats can ask for one more.  Two per side overall is the total allowed by law here.
<br />

<br />
All this proves is that the margin of error of our voting is becoming important, and we suck at margin of error.  What is the margin of error in voting?  Most of you hope it is in the 0.1% area, but our first MACHINE recount (they just reran them through counting machines) proved that to be seriously optomistic for several important counties.  Some counties had margins of error well over 1%.  Many of these recounts, if done alone, would have changed the election outcome.
<br />

<br />
The most interesting part of this recount is that I have never heard once that the Republican candidate wants to ensure that they count all of the votes, but the Democratic candidate specifically said that "If we can't recount them all, I don't want to recount any of them"... or something very near that.  In fact, I have never heard a Republican anywhere say that they should ensure that the count is the most accurate that it can be.  Why is that?
<br />

<br />
Just once, I'd like to hear a Republican stand up for voters and say "Count them all!!  Count them right, and ensure that the outcome is correct!"  That would raise my view of them immeasurably, but I just haven't seen it yet.  Anywhere.  Why?  All I hear is that "We counted them once, that ought to be enough!"  Why?
<br />

<br />
Anyone who understands either statistics or politics understands that for a vote to be believed, it must be BELIEVED beyond the margin of error of the vote.  They must eliminate the doubt, and in cases where there are either statistically insignificant differences (WA State) or statistical anomalies (Ohio), it is not wrong to use legal processes to evaluate these differences.
<br />

<br />
What are you afraid of if you are against counting more carefully?  The truth?
<br />

<br />
Ozbee
<br />
...not afraid of the truth, unless I am staring it in the mirror.  Damn, I'm ugly.  But at least I don't look like either a Donkey or an Elephant, despite what you think.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
