			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">If the parties in question are willing to put the money on the table for the recount, and follow the existing policies in place, I have absolutely no issue with having as many recounts as time allows. Even simultaneous recounts.  The goal here HAS TO BE accuracy.  If the recount is done properly, the results should be consistent, and the whiners will be out their money.  OTOH, if the recount changes things( no matter how unlikely that is), I would rather have the red flags raised, and see to it that an accurate count occurs.
<br />

<br />
Why not?  If the initial election was done right a recount will not change anything, and if it was not done right then I would like to know that and have it fixed by the appropriate authorities.  I'd say that regardless of who won, in whatever state, and whatever race was involved.  What I want is a proper election, and if my candidate of choice looses, then so be it.  
<br />

<br />
Eidolon, that election( WA state Governors race) was won by a margin of 162 votes in a machine count, and by 42 votes in a machine recount.  This is on a vote pool of ~3million votes.  Even a small error rate could shift it either way, having someone recount it is no loss for anyone involved, and personally I'd trust a audited manual recount more than the machines. The error margin here is tiny even an adjustment of 1/500th of 1% could significantly affect results. I do not predict that the results will change, but to be sure this is accurate we need to have an error rate that is extremely low.  At the moment an audited hand count is the best way to do this.
<br />

<br />
The other recounts(Ohio, etc.)  strike me as being vanity recounts.  They may well reveal something, but I doubt it.  If they reveal nothing then my confidence in the election improves, and if they reveal something, I'd rather find out about fraud than be happy in not knowing.  I do not understand why anyone would not be willing to allow such recounts.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
