				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Eidolon,
<br />
  You are so special.  I just love the way you lead into any discussion with the demeaning accusatory (and wholly unfounded):
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Put the kool-aid down and back slowly away.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
...or some similar blather.  Just attempt to dismiss a reasonable discussion with a big enough pile of horsecrap and you win, right?  Not in my reality.  Come join me in a reality that actually interacts with people, not just  rats and things located in your mother's basement.  It just might be fun. (I couldn't resist stooping to his level for just a second... sorry.  And see, I can be wittay, too!!!)
<br />

<br />
  First of all, how do we know how close any elective race is without examining it closely.  If they counted it accurately, you have "0'' (zero, nada, zip, ump-de-squat) to worry about.  But you still seem worried about a close review of a vote count.  Why?
<br />

<br />
  As far as Washington's recounts go, the first one was not a review of all of the ballots to ensure that this 'voter intent' state counted votes accurately.  It was just a recount of the ballots by machines.  And the recount that is going on now is wholly paid for by the requestor and if nothing changes, nothing changes except the requestor is out 700k+ American dollars.  Cha-ching...
<br />
  If things change, then things change.  First, the requestor gets their money back; if not, then they go broker faster.  Then, the other candidate can request another recount, at their expense, with the same financial outcome.  In the end, both candidates can spend up to 2 recounts (and their own money) doing this to ensure that the counting is truly accurate.
<br />

<br />
And oh, by the way, you said:
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Don't use words like "Statistically meaningful" when clearly you have ZERO idea what they mean.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
  I actually do know what 'statistically meaningful' is, and I'm positive that I am at least a bit better at grasping that concept than you.  Statistically meaningful results would produce results that exceed any 'margin of error' that may have been produced by the counting process.  The only way, THE ONLY WAY, to verify that is through a more careful recount.  Halffast (or half assed) guesses on what might have been without such a recount are just that.  Guesses.
<br />

<br />
Ozbee
<br />
...guesses that Eidolon has a favorite rat or 3 that he is snuggling into beastiality right now.  Only a recount will tell for sure.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
