			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Ozbee wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> if nothing changes, nothing changes except the requestor is out 700k+ American dollars.  Cha-ching....</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">Not eactly true. There is opportiunity cost as well.
<br />
Usually the winner has aproximately 2 months to figure out transition, invite people to give imput, invite people to quit their day jobs to join commitees, and plan transition into office so they hit the floor running. Below are just a few of the other costs involved in protracted election recounts.
<br />

<br />
If I told you, you MIGHT be getting a job in 2 months that would last maybe 4yrs, so get it together, get people on board, make big plans and get commitment to rolling on the date you MIGHT report to work. It will be harder to get people to quit their other jobs and make big time and energy commitments to join you in your planning for a project you MIGHT get.
<br />

<br />
The people on the current 'behind' candidate side that have been invited to join that person IF the recount changes sides now are in limbo as well.
<br />

<br />
There is the angst caused to all the voters hanging waiting and waiting for the recount times. There comes a point where people get so frustrated waiting for recounts they finally just want a winner to be declared and dont care who it is. Angst per person x total amount of voters in your state is a LOT of angst.
<br />

<br />
Current legeslature may put some work on hold waiting to see who wins, to know what will and wont be able to practically be NOT vetoed.
<br />

<br />
The news media can be distracted from other possibly more relavant issues.
<br />

<br />
You can argue that complete validity of election is worth all the extra costs involved. But there ARE many other costs as well involved in having recounts run up to the day before office transition.
<br />

<br />
I agree having a completely verifiable and trusted system in the first place solves all these problems, but the financial cost of the recount is too simplistic a view, it is not the only cost and may not be the biggest cost.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
