				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Yeah, Aabe.  It's a horrible tragedy when people actually use the laws as written (which is what the recount is doing in my state) to try to get an accurate result.  The angst it must be causing the average voter will have a terrible toll on Washington society.  Just wait and watch the suicides spike in December and January here (newsflash... they always spike in D&J here = it's a gray, and rainy, and Christmas thing...).
<br />

<br />
  The only ones that have angst not only can handle it, but deserve it.  There can be no excuse that I can imagine that would justify not making sure that who the voters actually voted into office gets that office.  Rep or Demo, it still is more important to get it right than get it over.  If you don't belive that, than I have no argument that could persuade you to give up the quick fix for the truth.
<br />

<br />
  All I want is the truth (or truth be told a tie... what a beautiful wakeup call for all of those 'my vote doesn't count so why bother' types).  We have yet to come close to the 'true' count here.  Two machine counts that do not take into account the laws that make this state a voter intient state and not a machine capability state.  After less than 50,000 of the votes were recounted,  they already had enough difference in votes (59 new found votes total) to prove that 42 votes weren't that significant.
