<br />

<br />
The topic of the thread however, is the recounts in Ohio.  Scroll up if you don't believe me.
<br />

<br />
Ozbee obviously got slightly confused about which election we were talking about.  It's hardly surprising given how confused he is about everything else.  
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">First of all, the Presidential Race was nowhere near as close as the Gubernatorial race you refer to. A recount in the US Presidential race makes absolutely no sense at all. Especially coming from that retarded hack, McAuliffe. 
<br />

<br />
With a margin of victory as slim as the Gubernatorial race in Washington, then yeah, a recount makes sense. ONE recount.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I'd buy into an automated manual recount...maybe.  It certainly has the potential to be more accurate than a machine optical scanner.  Unfortunately, it also has the potential for both human error and human sabotage.  Witness the Florida manual recounts of 2000...some of the counters had clear axes to grind when a ballot was "questionable".  I'm leery of opening up that can of worms.  And lets face it...third party auditors really worked wonders at Enron, didn't they?
<br />

<br />
The main problem I have with manual recounts can ultimately be summed up with the classical proverb "And who shall guard the guardians?".</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
