			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">This thread seems to be about recounts in general. The law has very specific mechanisms in place in re recounts.  It is my opinion that should the conditions of that law for the undertaking of a recount be met -- whatever those conditions may be -- then a recount should be undertaken.  If my guy wins/ loses/ or is declared an idiot by public referendum then so be it.  The recounts are a vital safeguard, and it is much better to do them more than needed than run the risk of not having a needed count. Yes there are personal costs to doing them.  However, most of them those procedures are set in state constitutions.  If the people want them changed then so be it -- amend the state constitution(s) of the affected states.  We have no grounds for chalenging the laws once they are invoked. -- we may feel that they are being used wastefully, or are inefficient laws, but that is something that should be addressed legislatively not in the court of the media.
<br />

<br />
WA -- MUST be recounted -- the vote is simply too close to trust to anything but an audited hand recount -- preferably with representatives from all parties present.
<br />

<br />
OH-- yeah, this is a vanity recount, and will probably change nothing. However, it was legaly constituted recount, so like it or lump it.  Change the laws/state constitution if you desire, but anything else is not acceptable.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
